ief in every sector comes the potential for new dialogues across previously impermeable policy and disciplinary silos. This volume brings together leading international authors to critically consider these challenges within legal and policy frameworks, including security and cohesion, welfare, law, health and social care, inequality, cohesion, extremism, migration and abuse. It challenges policy makers to re-imagine religion and belief as an integral part of public life that contains resources, practices, forms of knowledge and experience that are essential to a coherent policy approach to diversity, enhanced democracy and participation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0a.Religion and sociology. 0aSocial policy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaman, Lori G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrett, Mark G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCloke, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrisp, Beth R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCrisp, Beth R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavie, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinham, Adam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDinham, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeis-Peters, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScharbrodt, Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVickers, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re